\section[Electromagnetic Waves in Conductors]{\color{red} Electromagnetic Waves in Conductors \color{black}}
Inside a conductor, free electrons will move due to the force of an electromagnetic wave and the electric field will induce a current. Thus the free charge density and free current density are in general non-zero inside a conductor.\\

Note here $\vec{J}_f = \sigma \vec{E}$. In a conductor, Maxwell's Equations become the followings:
\begin{align*}
\nabla \cdot \vec{E} = \frac{\rho_f}{\epsilon} \qquad \nabla \times \vec{E} = \frac{\partial \vec{B}}{\partial t} \qquad \nabla \cdot \vec{B} =0\qquad \nabla \times \vec{B} = \mu \sigma \vec{E} + \mu \epsilon \frac{\partial \vec{E}}{\partial t}
\end{align*}
Note that a conductor may have different values of $\epsilon$ and $\mu$ compared to vacuum. \\

The continuity equation of the charge conservation requires the following holds:
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial \rho_f}{\partial t} = -\nabla \cdot \vec{J}_f = -\nabla \cdot (\sigma \vec{E}) = -\frac{\sigma}{\epsilon} \rho_f \qquad \Rightarrow \qquad \rho_f(t) = \rho_f(0)e^{-\sigma t/\epsilon } \tag{DC}
\end{align*}
where $\sigma $ is the conductivity of the conductor, and $\epsilon$ is the permittivity of the conductor. That is, equation (DC) suggests that any initial free charge $\rho_f(0)$ on the conductor dissipates in a characteristic time $\tau = \epsilon/\sigma$. \\

For a perfect conductor, we have $\sigma = \infty$, and hence $\tau = 0$, so there is no free charge density inside a perfect conductor. The natural time scale of an electromagnetic wave is its period, or $\frac{2\pi}{\omega}$, thus $\tau$ and $\frac{1}{\omega}$ afford a measure of goodness of a conductor:
\begin{enumerate}
\item For good conductors, we should have $\tau = \frac{\epsilon}{\sigma} << \frac{1}{\omega}$, or $\omega\epsilon << \sigma$
\item For poor conductors,  we should have $\tau = \frac{\epsilon}{\sigma} >> \frac{1}{\omega}$, or $\omega\epsilon >> \sigma$
\end{enumerate}
Note here the goodness of a conductor is frequency dependent, and it could be a good conductor at low frequencies but a poor conductor at high frequencies. \\

Ignoring the transient behavior, that is, after all free charge disappear and therefore $\rho_f = 0$, Maxwell's Equations become the followings:
\begin{align*}
\nabla \cdot \vec{E} = 0 \qquad \nabla \times \vec{E} = \frac{\partial \vec{B}}{\partial t} \qquad \nabla \cdot \vec{B} =0\qquad \nabla \times \vec{B} = \mu \sigma \vec{E} + \mu \epsilon \frac{\partial \vec{E}}{\partial t}
\end{align*}
with the exception of additional term in $\nabla \times \vec{B}$, these equations are the same as those for nonconducting media. \\

By applying curl to $\nabla \times \vec{E}$ and $\nabla \times \vec{B}$, one can obtain the modified wave equations:
\begin{align*}
\nabla^2 \vec{E} = \mu \epsilon \frac{\partial^2 \vec{E}}{\partial t^2} + \mu \sigma \frac{\partial \vec{E}}{\partial t} \qquad\qquad\qquad \nabla^2 \vec{B} = \mu \epsilon \frac{\partial^2 \vec{B}}{\partial t^2} + \mu \sigma \frac{\partial \vec{B}}{\partial t} \tag{MWE}
\end{align*}
Note here PDE (MWE) reduces to the usual wave equation when $\sigma = 0$ for insulators. \\
PDE (MWE) have plane wave solutions given by the followings:
\begin{align*}
\vt{E}(z,t) = \that{E}_0 e^{i(\that{k}z-\omega t)} \qquad\qquad\qquad \vt{B}(z,t) = \vt{B}_0 e^{i(\that{k}z-\omega t)}
\end{align*}
with a complex wave number $\that{k}$, which satisfies:
\begin{align*}
\that{k}^2 = \mu \epsilon \omega^2 + i \mu \sigma \omega
\end{align*}
Denote $\Re({\that{k}}) = k$ and $\Im({\that{k}}) = \kappa$, we can write:
\begin{align*}
k = \omega \sqrt{\frac{\mu \epsilon}{2}}\sqrt{\sqrt{1+ \left( \frac{\sigma}{\epsilon \omega}\right)}+1}\qquad\qquad\qquad \kappa = \omega \sqrt{\frac{\mu \epsilon}{2}}\sqrt{\sqrt{1+ \left( \frac{\sigma}{\epsilon \omega}\right)}-1}
\end{align*}
For a good conductor, we have $\sigma >> \epsilon \omega$, hence we get:
\begin{align*}
\that{k}^2 = \mu \epsilon \omega^2 + i \mu \sigma \omega \approx i \mu \sigma \omega  \qquad \Rightarrow \qquad k \approx \kappa \approx \omega \sqrt{\frac{\mu \epsilon}{2}\frac{\sigma}{\epsilon \omega}} = \sqrt{\frac{\mu \sigma \omega}{2}}
\end{align*}
For a poor conductor, we have $\sigma << \epsilon \omega$, hence we get:
\begin{align*}
\that{k}^2 = \mu \epsilon \omega^2 + i \mu \sigma \omega = \mu \epsilon \omega^2\left(1+ i \frac{\sigma}{\epsilon \omega}\right)\qquad \Rightarrow \qquad k \approx \sqrt{\mu \epsilon}\omega  = \frac{\omega}{\nu} \quad \text{and}\quad \kappa \approx \frac{\sigma}{2}\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{\epsilon}}
\end{align*}
The imaginary part of $\that{k}$ results in an attenuation of the wave inside a conductor. \\

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.26]{EMinCond.png}
\end{center}

That is, we can write:
\begin{align*}
\vt{E}(z,t) = \vt{E}_0 e^{-\kappa z} e^{i(kz-\omega t)} \qquad\qquad\qquad \vt{B}(z,t)=\vt{B}_0 e^{-\kappa z}e^{i(kz-\omega t)}
\end{align*}
The real part describes the wave propagation with the wavelength and speed given by:
\begin{align*}
\lambda = \frac{2\pi}{k} \qquad\qquad\qquad \nu=\frac{\omega}{k}
\end{align*}
The distance into a conductor it takes to reduce the amplitude by a factor of $\frac{1}{e}$ is called the skin depth, denoted as $d$, that is, we have:
\begin{align*}
d = \frac{1}{\kappa}
\end{align*}
For a good conductor, we have:
\begin{align*}
d \approx \sqrt{\frac{2}{\mu \sigma \omega}} \qquad\qquad\qquad \frac{1}{\kappa}\approx \frac{1}{k} = \frac{\lambda}{2\pi}
\end{align*}
\hfill\break
\example\\
Communication with submarines using electromagnetic waves is challenging because the relative good conductivity of sea water $\sigma \approx 5\, S/m$. Extreme low frequency (ELF)  radio waves $3\, Hz\,\ \sim\ 300\, Hz$  can penetrate sea water to depths of around $100\, m$. But building transmitter is a formidable challenge because of its long wavelength.\\

On the other hand, sound waves travel far in sea water, therefore, acoustic signals or sonar is widely used for undersea communication.\\

Maxwell's Equations still ensure the electromagnetic wave in conductors to be transverse. $\vec{E}$ and $\vec{B}$ are still related in one another by Maxwell's Equations in conductors. Choosing the $x$-axis to be along the direction of polarization, we can write the following:
\begin{align*}
\vt{E}(z,t) = \that{E}_0 e^{-\kappa z} e^{i(kz-\omega t)}\hat{x} \qquad\qquad\qquad \vt{B}(z,t)=\frac{\vec{\that{k}}\times \vt{E}}{\omega} = \frac{\that{k}}{\omega}\that{E}_0 e^{-\kappa z} e^{i(kz-\omega t)}\hat{y}
\end{align*} 
To understand the implication of $\that{k}$ in the complex amplitude of the magnetic field, we write it in terms of modulus and phase:
\begin{align*}
\that{k} = Ke^{i\phi} \qquad \text{with }K = \sqrt{k^2 + \kappa^2} \ \ \text{ and }\tan(\phi) = \frac{\kappa}{k}
\end{align*}
The complex amplitudes of electric and magnetic fields have the relationships given by the following:
\begin{align*}
\that{E}_0 = E_0 e^{i\delta_E} \qquad \that{B}_0 = B_0 e^{i\delta_B}\qquad \Rightarrow \qquad B_0 e^{i \delta_B} = \frac{K}{\omega}E_0 e^{i(\delta_E + \phi)}
\end{align*}
here evidently, $\vec{E}$ and $\vec{B}$ are no longer in phase, and $\delta_B - \delta_E = \phi$, and we have:
\begin{align*}
\frac{B_0}{E_0} = \frac{K}{\omega} = \sqrt{\mu \epsilon \sqrt{1+ \left( \frac{\sigma}{\epsilon \omega}\right)^2}} = \frac{1}{\nu}\left( 1+ \left( \frac{\sigma}{\epsilon\omega}\right)^2\right)^{1/4}
\end{align*}

The actual wave is described by the real electric and magnetic fields, which can be modeled as the followings:
\begin{align*}
\vec{E}(z,t) = E_0 e^{\kappa z} \cos(kz-\omega t+ \delta_E) \hat{x} \qquad \qquad \qquad \vec{B}(z,t)=\frac{K}{\omega}E_0e^{-\kappa z}\cos(kz-\omega t + \delta_E + \phi) \hat{y}
\end{align*}
For good conductor, we have $\sigma >> \epsilon \omega$, we have the following holds:
\begin{align*}
\sigma_B - \sigma_E = \phi \approx \frac{\pi}{4} \qquad \qquad \frac{B_0}{E_0}\approx \frac{1}{\nu}\sqrt{\frac{\sigma}{\epsilon \omega}}
\end{align*}
The magnetic field lags the electric field by $\pi/4$, but both fields attenuate rapidly and diminish after about a depth of one wavelength. \\

