\section[Reflection on a Conducting Surface]{\color{red} Reflection on a Conducting Surface\color{black}}
While the volume charge dissipates quickly in a conductor, there are in general charges and currents on a conducting surface due to an electromagnetic wave. Boundary conditions at a conducting surface are therefore given by the followings:
\begin{align*}
\epsilon_1 E_1^{\perp} - \epsilon_e E_2^{\perp} = \sigma_f \qquad B_1^{\perp} - B_2^{\perp} = 0\qquad \vec{E}_1^{\parallel} - \vec{E}_2^{\parallel} = 0 \qquad \frac{\vec{B}_1^{\parallel}}{\mu_1} - \frac{\vec{B}_2^{\parallel}}{\mu_2} = \vec{K}_f \times \vec{n}
\end{align*}
where $\vec{n}$ is the normal vector of the surface, $\parallel$ denote the component of the quantity that is parallel to the surface, and $\perp$ denote the quantity that is perpendicular to the surface. $\epsilon_i$ and $\mu_i$ are the permittivity and permeability of the linear materials, respectively, and $\sigma_f$ is the free surface charge density.\\

For an Ohmic conductor, we have:
\begin{align*}
\vec{J}_f = \sigma \vec{E}
\end{align*}
where $\sigma$ is the conductivity, and the surface current density $\vec{K}_f\approx 0$, unless the electric field is extremely large at the surface, so we will assume $\vec{K}_f = 0$ in the following derivation. \\

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.28]{ReflecConduc.png}
\end{center}

Now let the $z=0$ plane be the interface, consider a monochromatic plane with its polarization in the $x$-direction incidents on the surface from the the negative $z$-direction, given by the following:
\begin{align*}
\vt{E}_I(z,t) = \vt{E}_{I0}e^{i(k_1 z -\omega t)}\hat{x} \qquad\qquad\qquad \vt{B}_{I}(z,t) = \frac{\vt{E}_{I0}}{\nu_1} e^{i(k_1 z-\omega t)}\hat{y}
\end{align*}
We also get the corresponding reflected and transmitted waves as the followings:
\begin{align*}
\vt{E}_{R}(z,t) = \that{E}_{R0}e^{i(-k_1z - \omega t)}\hat{x} \qquad \qquad \qquad  \vt{B}_R(z,t) = -\frac{\that{E}_{R0}}{\nu_1}e^{i(-k_1 z - \omega t)}\, \hat{y}
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
\vt{E}_{T}(z,t) = \that{E}_{T0}e^{i(-k_2z - \omega t)}\hat{x} \qquad \qquad \qquad  \vt{B}_T(z,t) = -\frac{\that{E}_{T0}}{\omega}e^{i(-k_1 z - \omega t)}\, \hat{y}
\end{align*}
Since neither $\vec{E}$ and $\vec{B}$ has component perpendicular to the surface of incidence, by the boundary conditions, we get $\sigma_f = 0$, and the following holds:
\begin{align*}
\that{E}_{I0} + \that{E}_{R0} = \that{E}_{T0} \qquad \qquad \that{E}_{I0} - \that{E}_{R0} = \that{\beta}\that{E}_{T0}\qquad \text{with }\that{\beta} = \frac{\mu_1 \nu_1}{\mu_2(\omega /\that{k}_2} = \frac{\mu_1\nu_1}{\mu_2 \omega}\that{k}_2
\end{align*}
Solving for the complex amplitudes of the reflected and transmitted waves, we get:
\begin{align*}
\that{E}_{R0} = \left( \frac{1-\that{\beta}}{1+\that{\beta}}\right) \that{E}_{I0} \qquad\qquad\qquad \that{E}_{T0} = \left(\frac{2}{1+\that{\beta}}\right)\that{E}_{I0}
\end{align*}
For a good conductor, we have $\sigma >> \epsilon \omega$, and hence we can write:
\begin{align*}
\that{\beta} = \frac{\mu_1 \nu_1}{\mu_2 \omega} \that{k}_2 >>1 \qquad \Rightarrow \qquad \that{E}_{R0} = - \that{E}_{I0} \text{ and }\that{E}_{T0} = 0
\end{align*}
The wave is totally reflected with a $\pi$ phase shift. This is the reason that a good conductor also makes a good mirror.\\

\example The skin depth of silver for visible light is about $10\, nm$, therefore a thin coating on the back of glass is sufficient to make a good conductor. The kin depth of silver for visible light is around $-5\, nm$.\\

