\section[Dispersion]{\color{red} Dispersion\color{black}}
The propagation of electromagnetic waves through matter is governed by the three properties of a material, (1) the permittivity $\epsilon$, (2) the permeability $\mu$, and (3) the conductivity $\sigma$ of the material. We have assumed so far these parameters are independent of the wave frequency. In reality, all of them depend on the frequency of the wave to some extend.\\

For most of the non-conducting material, we have $\mu \approx \mu_0$, and $\sigma \approx 0$. The electromagnetic wave propagation is determined by $\epsilon$, or the index of refraction $n \approx \sqrt{\epsilon_r}$. It is well known that $n$ is wavelength dependent, a property responsible for phenomena such as rainbows or color splitting by a prism. \\

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.2]{IndexRefrac.png}
\end{center}

The phenomenon, the wavelength or frequency dependence of the refractive index $n$, is called dispersion. The medium with this property is called dispersive.\\

For most transparent material, the wavelength of dependence of $n$ can be parametrized as the following:
\begin{align*}
n(\lambda) = 1 + A \left( 1 + \frac{B}{\lambda^2}\right) \tag{CSF}
\end{align*}
Equation (CSF) is known as the Cauchy's Formula. The material-dependent parameters $A$ and $B$ are called the coefficients of refraction and dispersion, respectively. \\

\newpage
\section[Wave Packet and Group Velocity]{\color{red}Wave Packet and Group Velocity\color{black}}
An idealized plane wave of a singular frequency extends to the  entire space. A localized wave packet is a superposition of many  plane waves of different frequencies.\\

Since waves of different frequency travel at different speeds in a dispersive medium,  a localized wave packet will change shape as it propagates. For example, a sharply localized packet will flatten out.\\

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.16]{wavePacket2.png}
\end{center}


While each sinusoidal component, crests and troughs, travels at the ordinary wave, or phase, velocity:
\begin{align*}
\nu = \nu_0 = \frac{\omega}{k} = \frac{c}{n}
\end{align*}
The wave packet as a whole, the envelope, moves at the group velocity:
\begin{align*}
\nu_g = \frac{d\omega}{dk} = \frac{d}{dk}\left( \frac{ck}{n}\right) = \frac{c}{n} - \frac{ck}{n^2}\frac{dn}{dk}
\end{align*}
The function $\omega(k)$, or $n(\omega)$, is called the dispersion relation. \\

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.15]{wavePackage.png}
\end{center}

In quantum mechanics, particles are represented by wave packets and therefore the group velocity is particle's velocity.
